CONTRACT DEFINITION:
1. RESEARCH NOTE: See architecture/fix_design.md §Bug 4 and architecture/bug_cascade_map.md Bug 6. findEnv (extdir.go:85-99) validates with os.Stat (FOLLOWS symlinks) but returns filepath.Abs(val) (does NOT resolve symlinks — deliberately, per the doc comment at extdir.go:11-14). discover.Index (index.go:44) calls filepath.Abs then os.Stat (which follows the symlink and passes the IsDir guard). But filepath.WalkDir (index.go:57) internally calls os.Lstat on the root, sees ModeSymlink (not a dir), and walks NOTHING. Result: --path prints the dir (exit 0), --list says 'no extensions found' (exit 1). The existing test TestFindEnvDoesNotResolveSymlinks (extdir_test.go:201) asserts findEnv does NOT EvalSymlinks — fixing in Index (NOT findEnv) keeps that test valid.
2. INPUT: `extensionsDir` (the path passed to Index, possibly a symlink). `root` from filepath.Abs(extensionsDir) at index.go:44.
3. LOGIC: After `root, err := filepath.Abs(extensionsDir)` (index.go:44) and BEFORE `info, err := os.Stat(root)` (index.go:48), add:
   ```go
   // Resolve symlinks on the walk root. filepath.WalkDir Lstats the root
   // and will not descend a symlinked directory (stdlib default). os.Stat
   // below follows the symlink and passes the IsDir guard, but WalkDir then
   // sees ModeSymlink and walks nothing — producing an empty catalog.
   if resolved, rerr := filepath.EvalSymlinks(root); rerr == nil {
       root = resolved
   }
   ```
   This is a no-op for non-symlinked paths (EvalSymlinks returns the same path). If EvalSymlinks fails (e.g. broken symlink chain), fall through to os.Stat which will also fail and propagate the error normally. No mocking needed.
4. OUTPUT: Index walks the resolved target directory for symlinked roots. --list, --search, tag resolution, and check all work for a symlinked weave_EXTENSIONS_DIR. --path still shows the original symlink path (it uses extdir.Find() directly, not discover.Index()). Extension.Path and Extension.EntryFile point to the resolved target (the real filesystem location), which is correct for pi -e consumption.
5. DOCS: [Mode A] Add an inline comment in index.go Index() explaining the symlink resolution and why it is in Index (not findEnv). This rides WITH the work.
6. TESTS (implicit TDD): Add TestIndexSymlinkedRoot — create a real dir with a foo.ts extension, symlink the dir, call Index on the symlink path. Assert len(got)==1, got[0].RelTag=="foo". Guard with `if err := os.Symlink(realDir, link); err != nil { t.Skipf('symlinks not supported: %v', err) }`. Use t.TempDir() and writeFile helper.

CONTRACT DEFINITION:
1. RESEARCH NOTE: See architecture/fix_design.md §Bug 2. ExtractJSDoc (internal/discover/jsdoc.go:135-141) single-line branch (`case i == startIdx && i == closeIdx`). Current code: `rest := strings.TrimPrefix(line, "/**")` then `strings.Index(rest, "*/")`. For input "/**/": TrimPrefix("/**/", "/**") = "/" (the opener /** consumed pos 0-2, but the closer */ starts at pos 2 — they OVERLAP). Index("/", "*/") = -1 (no closer found in the remainder). The stray "/" is kept as content and returned as the description. All other empty forms (/** */ etc.) work correctly because they have a space between opener and closer.
2. INPUT: `line` string — the first non-blank line of the file, guaranteed by steps 5-6 of ExtractJSDoc to start with exactly "/**" (not "/***") and to contain "*/" somewhere. `startIdx == closeIdx` (this is the single-line case — opener and closer are on the same line).
3. LOGIC: Replace the current single-line branch with position-based extraction that operates on the ORIGINAL line:
   ```go
   case i == startIdx && i == closeIdx:
       // Single-line block: extract content between opener "/**" (len 3)
       // and closer "*/" on the ORIGINAL line. Finding "*/" first avoids
       // the degenerate case where opener and closer overlap (e.g. "/**/"
       // has "*/" at position 2, which is within the opener's 3 chars).
       c := strings.Index(line, "*/")
       if c <= 3 {
           // "*/" starts at or before the opener ends -> empty content
           // (opener /** ends at index 3 exclusive; closer at c means overlap).
           line = ""
       } else {
           line = line[3:c] // content strictly between "/**" and "*/"
       }
   ```
   Trace for "/**/": c=2, 2<=3 -> line="". Correct.
   Trace for "/** desc */": c=9, 9>3 -> line[3:9]=" desc " -> stripStarPrefix -> TrimSpace -> "desc". Correct.
   Trace for "/**desc*/": c=7, 7>3 -> line[3:7]="desc". Correct.
   Trace for "/** */": c=4, 4>3 -> line[3:4]=" " -> stripStarPrefix(" ") = "" (TrimLeft) -> dropped. Correct.
   No mocking needed.
4. OUTPUT: ExtractJSDoc returns "" for "/**/" (was "/"). Returns "desc" for "/** desc */" and "/**desc*/" (unchanged). Returns "" for "/** */" (unchanged). All existing TestExtractJSDoc cases continue to pass.
5. DOCS: [Mode A] Update the single-line branch comment in jsdoc.go (~line 135-136) to explain why we find "*/" on the original line before extracting content (opener/closer overlap in degenerate blocks). This rides WITH the work.
6. TESTS (implicit TDD): Add {"empty-block-degenerate", "/**/\n", ""} to the TestExtractJSDoc table. Verify all existing cases in the table still pass. Optionally add {"empty-block-space", "/** */\n", ""} to confirm the space variant is not affected.

CONTRACT DEFINITION:
1. RESEARCH NOTE: See architecture/fix_design.md §Bug 5 and architecture/bug_cascade_map.md Bug 3 (the check WARN issue). After P1.M1.T1.S1 (Bug 1 fix), a package.json with at least one EXISTING pi.extensions entry is classified as a package by classifyDir case (a) and never reaches appendEmptyFolderFindings. Only the ALL-missing case falls through: classifyDir cases a (no existing entry) -> b (JSON valid, no perr) -> c/d (no index.*) -> e (plain dir, descend) -> discover.Index returns 0 entries -> appendEmptyFolderFindings (check.go:287-312) emits WARN 'empty category folder: <name>'. VERIFIED: the check package CAN range over `pkg.Pi.Extensions` (type discover.lenientAnySlice = []any) from external code — confirmed by compilation test. The check package does NOT currently have a fileExists helper; discover.fileExists and extdir.fileExists are unexported duplicates.
2. INPUT: `child` string (the top-level subdir path being checked), from the appendEmptyFolderFindings loop in check.go. `discover.ParsePackageJSON(child)` returns (pkg discover.PackageJSON, hasPkg bool, perr error). `pkg.Pi.Extensions` is []any (rangeable; each element is an `any` that may be a string). `sub` ([]discover.Extension) from `discover.Index(child)` — already computed at check.go:298; `len(sub) == 0` triggers the empty-folder path.
3. LOGIC: Add a helper function to check.go:
   ```go
   func fileExists(path string) bool {
       info, err := os.Stat(path)
       return err == nil && !info.IsDir()
   }
   func allMissingPiExtensions(dir string) []string {
       pkg, hasPkg, perr := discover.ParsePackageJSON(dir)
       if !hasPkg || perr != nil { return nil }
       var missing []string
       hasAny := false
       for _, e := range pkg.Pi.Extensions {
           s, ok := e.(string)
           if !ok { continue }
           hasAny = true
           if !fileExists(filepath.Join(dir, s)) {
               missing = append(missing, s)
           } else {
               return nil // at least one exists -> not all-missing
           }
       }
       if !hasAny { return nil }
       return missing
   }
   ```
   In appendEmptyFolderFindings, BEFORE the WARN (when len(sub) == 0), call allMissingPiExtensions(child). If it returns non-nil, append an ExtensionReport with Finding{LevelError, "pi.extensions entry does not exist: " + strings.Join(missing, ", ")} and `continue` (skip the WARN). The existing WARN path stays for dirs with no package.json.
4. OUTPUT: check.Check returns HasErrors()==true (exit 1 via main) for a store containing a top-level dir whose package.json has non-empty pi.extensions with ALL entries missing. The ERROR message names the missing entry paths. A dir with NO package.json still gets the WARN 'empty category folder' (unchanged). A dir with a parseable package.json but EMPTY pi.extensions still gets the WARN (unchanged — empty pi.extensions is not a broken reference).
5. DOCS: [Mode A] Update the appendEmptyFolderFindings doc comment (check.go:~line 276) to note the pi.extensions all-missing ERROR check that precedes the empty-folder WARN. This rides WITH the work.
6. TESTS (implicit TDD): Add TestCheckAllMissingPiExtensionsIsError — root has a top-level dir 'badpkg' with package.json {"name":"badpkg","pi":{"extensions":["./missing.ts"]}} and NO entry files. Assert rep.HasErrors()==true, rep.Errors>=1, and finding(rep, "pi.extensions entry does not exist") returns a Finding with Level==LevelError. Also assert the WARN 'empty category folder' is NOT present for badpkg. Verify TestCheckEmptyCategoryFolder still passes (a dir with NO package.json still gets the WARN). Use the lower-level fixture pattern from TestCheckUnparseablePackageJSON (write files directly + findExt or discover.Index).
